<div id="review_768183192" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/768183192" />
    <a title="Brad Lyerla" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4384303-brad-lyerla"><img alt="Brad Lyerla" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620760804p2/4384303.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/768183192?book_show_action=true">Nov 18, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brad Lyerla" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brad Lyerla" href="/user/show/4384303-brad-lyerla">Brad Lyerla</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780226500447" href="/book/show/364540.The_Prince">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer768183192" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17066490811777553061">THE PRINCE is nothing more than a manual for acquiring and maintaining power. It reminds one of the scenes in Coppola&apos;s GODFATHER, where Vito Corleone instructs Michael how to consolidate his power after Vito is gone and the other families come after the Corleone family. Even given Machiavelli’s modest aims for this book, I cannot tell if the advice he offers is sound. <br/><br/>I do know that this book is important. It is the first account ever of how to do politics with no concern for nobility, happines</span>
  <span id="freeText17066490811777553061" style="display:none">THE PRINCE is nothing more than a manual for acquiring and maintaining power. It reminds one of the scenes in Coppola's GODFATHER, where Vito Corleone instructs Michael how to consolidate his power after Vito is gone and the other families come after the Corleone family. Even given Machiavelli’s modest aims for this book, I cannot tell if the advice he offers is sound. <br /><br />I do know that this book is important. It is the first account ever of how to do politics with no concern for nobility, happiness, godliness, morality or anything beyond maintaining the power and safety of the ruler. That difference represented a transformative break in the intellectual history of the West. <br /><br />It also begs the question whether this change was for the best? That’s a question for someone other than Machiavelli to answer, of course. <br /><br />Mansfield’s accompanying essay is excellent.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17066490811777553061" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


